	<div class="banner">
		<center><font color="white" size="16px" face="arial">ArsR</font></center>
	</div>
	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">ArsR transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>Details are shown in Supplementary Table S2 , but briefly this consisted of 184 genes that could be divided into the following categories : repressed by Fur , 63 ; activated by Fur , 15 ; repressed by CpxR , 21 ; activated by CpxR , 37 ; repressed by SoxS , 1 ; activated by SoxS , 23 ; repressed by OxyR , 2 ; activated by OxyR , 16 ; activated by CusR , 6 ; activated by BaeR , 9 ; repressed by Zur , 4 ; repressed by ArsR , 3 ; activated by ZraR , 3 ; activated by ZntR , 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22016571" target="_blank">22016571</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="ACT_collapse_similarity" for="act_similarity_2">
Statistical modelling of the transcriptomic data generated from the Zn shift focused on the role of ten key regulators ; ArsR , BaeR , CpxR , CusR , Fur , OxyR , SoxS , ZntR , ZraR and Zur .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22016571" target="_blank">22016571</a>]<br></label>
<input id="act_similarity_2", type="checkbox">
<div class="ACT_similar">
<li>The analysis of the transcriptomic data generated from the Zn shift focused on the role of ten key regulators : ArsR , BaeR , CpxR , CusR , Fur , OxyR , SoxS , ZntR , ZraR and Zur .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22016571" target="_blank">22016571</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Dimerization Is Essential for DNA Binding and Repression by the ArsR Metalloregulatory Protein of Escherichia coli * ( Received for publication , March 17 , 1997 , and in revised form , April 21 , 1997 ) Chun Xu and Barry P. Rosen ‡ From the Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology , Wayne State University School of Medicine , Detroit , Michigan 48201 Arsenical resistance ( ars ) operons produce resistance to trivalent and pentavalent salts of the metalloids arsenic and antimony in cells of Escherichia coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Role of Arsenic-Thiol Interactions in Metalloregulation of the ars Operon * ( Received for publication , January 4 , 1996 , and in revised form , February 6 , 1996 ) Weiping Shi ‡ , Jun Dong § , Robert A. Scott § , Marina Y. Ksenzenko ‡ , and Barry P. Rosen ‡ ¶ From the ‡ Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology , Wayne State University , School of Medicine , Detroit , Michigan 48201 and the § Center for Metalloenzyme Studies , University of Georgia , Athens , Georgia 30602-2556 The ars operon of the Escherichia coli plasmid R773 that confers arsenical and antimonial resistance is negatively regulated by the ArsR repressor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>We identiﬁed a high proportion of TFs belonging to the AsnC , ArsR , MarR , TetR/AcrR , BirA , AraC/XylS , Fur , LysR , and PhoU families in bacteria and archaea .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15556475" target="_blank">15556475</a>]<br></li>
<li>For instance , proteins classiﬁed in the Fur and PhoU families regulate iron and phosphate metabolism , the AsnC and MarR families belong to the earliest repressor super-group ( Pérez - Rueda and Collado-Vides , 2001 ) , while the ArsR family contains the shortest repressor proteins described so far ( Pérez - Rueda and Collado-Vides , 2000 ; Sato and Kobayashi , 1998 ) , very close in length to the proposed hypothetical ancestor of TFs .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15556475" target="_blank">15556475</a>]<br></li>
<li>Early reports on ArsR corroborated this hypothesis since substitution of one or both cysteines with non-met-al-liganding residues in the 30ELCVCD35 motif inhibited the ability of arsenate salts to dissociate ArsR from the ars O/P [ 46 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Chimeras in which the fusion sites were at residues 20 , 69 , 74 , and 79 of the ArsR proteins were produced in both arsenite-induced and uninduced cells , indicating that these chimeric proteins were constitutively expressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>Surprisingly , Cys61 of SmtB was previously found not to be essential for Zn ( II ) sensing in vivo , in contrast to Cys32 of ArsR [ 46,47 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Negative regulation of repressor ^ O/P binding by inducing metals The direct binding of metal ions to the regulatory ( K3N / K3 or K5/K5C ) sites of individual SmtB/ArsR repressors ( Fig. 6 ) results in strong inhibition or negative allosteric regulation of speci cents c O/P DNA binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>The O/P binding properties of other members of the SmtB/ArsR family , including the K5C sensor NmtR and the K3N sensor CadC , are also strongly negatively regulated by metal binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it is likely that the chromosomal ars operon is organized as a single transcription unit that is regulated by the arsenic - and antimony-inducible ArsR repressor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7721697" target="_blank">7721697</a>]<br></li>
<li>The arsR gene product , the ArsR repressor , was expressed and purified .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>plasmid-borne ars operons , transcription was controlled by the ArsR repressor , the product of the first gene of each operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>Tc determine the function of the ArsR protein , a genetic analysis of its role in regulation of ars expression was undertaken using fusions of the btaM gene to the arsR gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>There was no trans effect of a wild-type arsR gene on expression of the fusions in pCBR92 and pCBR104 , in which the chimeric ArsR proteins still functioned as repressors ( Fig. 3B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>Detailed investigation of the kinetics of metal binding and metal-induced dissociation of O/P-bound sensor proteins in the presence and absence of low molecular mass thiolates will be required to gain more insight into the mechanism of transcriptional control by SmtB/ArsR sensor proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>If dimerization is required for the metalloregulatory activity of ArsR , then there should be a correlation between the aggregation state of the protein and its ability to repress in the absence of inducer and derepress in the presence of inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of the gene for His6-tagged ArsR repressed lacZ expression in the absence of inducer and induced in the presence of sodium arsenite .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>It can be concluded , therefore , that arsfl expression is autoregulated : expression is repressed by ArsR in the absence of arsenical inducers and is induced in their presence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>ther alone , suggesting that bindingof endogenous amounts of A positiveselection was used to select formutants unrespon - ArsR protein prevents full induction from the lac promoter sive to inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051064" target="_blank">8051064</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since PAO can form only two arsenic -- thiol bonds with ArsR , dicoordinate binding must be sufficient for induction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since a third coordination is not possible with PAO , induction must require only two bonds between inducer and ligands in ArsR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>The mutations changed codon 32 from In Vitro Analysis of Inducer Interaction-The ars operator-TGC to TAC , codon 32 from TGC to TTC , and codon 34 from ArsR protein complex is dissociated by the additionof inducer TGT to TAT , producing amino acid changes C32Y , C32F , and ( 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051064" target="_blank">8051064</a>]<br></li>
<li>Using a novel selection for arsR mutants that encoded active repressors that were unable to be induced by arsenicals or antimonials , we previously isolated three hydroxylamine mutants in the codons for Cys-32 and Cys-34 , resulting in ArsR proteins C32Y , C32F , and C34Y ( Shi et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , while the Cys-37 thiolate is able to form a bond with As ( III ) , binding to the sulfurs of only Cys-32 and Cys-34 is required to produce the conformational change in ArsR that results in dissociation from the operator DNA and transcriptional derepression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Binding of ArsR Proteins to Immobilized Phenylarsine Oxide -- Although the effects of mutation of arsR indicated that Cys-32 and Cys-34 are required for induction , they do not eliminate the possibility that other residues interact with As ( III ) without producing the conformational change that results in dissociation from DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Metal Binding Properties of ArsR Repressors -- ArsR binds arsenite , antimonite , or the organoarsenical phenylarsine oxide through the cysteine thiolates of Cys-32 and Cys-34 ( 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArsR residues Cys-32 and Cys-34 were previously identified as involved in induction by arsenite and antimonite , suggesting coordination between As ( III ) and the two cysteine thiolates .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Using PAO affinity chromatography as an assay for arsenic-ArsR interaction , Cys-32 , Cys-34 , and Cys-37 were each found to be required for ArsR binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , ArsR proteins in which either Cys-32 or Cys-34 was altered to glycine still bound strongly to the PAO resin .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArsR proteins containing any two of the three cysteine residues Cys-32 , Cys-34 , and Cys-37 bound to the resin .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition to Cys-32 and Cys-34 , there are three other cysteine residues in the ArsR protein : Cys-37 , Cys-108 , and Cys-116 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>In fact , several repressor proteins in this family do utilize ligands from this ` box ' including ArsR and CadC proteins ; however , it is now known that this parallel can not be made to all other members of the family [ 39,45,46 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>To exclude the possibility that the phenotype of these ArsR derivatives resulted from the substitution of the bulky aromatic groups of tyrosine or phenylalanine for the two cysteine thiolates , these two cysteine residues in ArsR were changed to glycine residues , individually or together , by site-directed mutagenesis , producing three altered ArsR proteins : C32G , C34G , and C32G/C34G .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results indicate that the single and double glycine substitutions did not affect the ability of ArsR to repress its own synthesis , but did prevent these proteins from responding to inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Weaker , though still signiﬁcantly homologous , are the plasmid-encoded ArsR , ArsB , and ArsC proteins of both S. aureus and S. xylosus ( Fig. 2B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7721697" target="_blank">7721697</a>]<br></li>
<li>All three altered ArsR proteins still bound specifically to the ars operator , but inducers were considerably less effective in dissociating in vitro ArsR-DNA complexes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Wild-type and altered ArsR proteins were applied to the column , which was washed extensively to remove unbound proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArsR proteins with C32G , C34G , and C32G/C34G substitutions were active repressors , but were not inducible in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Autoregulation of ArsR proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcriptional activation of lacZ reporter indicated that dimerization of the ArsR is stable in yeast .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>In in vitro gel mobility shift assays , PAO dissociated the wild-type ArsR repressor at concentrations as low as 0.5 mM FIG. 3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Wild-type ArsR bound to the PAO resin with extremely high affinity , characteristic of a protein with a vicinal thiol pair .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>In Vitro DNA Binding Properties of Altered ArsR Proteins -- ArsR binds to a sequence immediately upstream of the ars promoter and can be dissociated with either As ( III ) or Sb ( III ) ( Wu and Rosen , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Similar results were obtained for C-terminal chimeras of R773 ArsR ( Wu and Rosen , 1991 ) , and those chimeras were shown to be bind to the promoter DNA as dimers ( Wu and Rosen , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>Similar chimeras in R773 ArsR were unable to-bind to DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>Alteration of Ser-43 to alanine or proline had no effect on ArsR function in vivo or in vitro , while alteration of Ser-48 resulted in constitutivity in vivo and decreased affinity of DNA in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>PAO is not only an effective inducer in vivo ; in in vitro DNA binding assays , ArsR exhibited 10 -- 100-fold higher affinity for this organic arsenical than for inorganic arsenite or antimonite .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>When the mature form of b-lactamase was fused to the ArsR protein at residue 92 , 101 , 104 , or 114 , expression of the chimeric protein was still inducible , indicating that residues 92 to the C terminus are not required for ArsR function .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>ZntR , a member of the ArsR family , regulates the expression of zntA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11831459" target="_blank">11831459</a>]<br></li>
<li>Determination of arsenic ligands in ArsR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>p-lactamase activity of ArsR fusions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>The 117-residue ArsR repressor purifies as a dimer ( 2 ) , and the dimeric form binds to DNA ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArsR Protein Is a DNA Binding Protein -- Gel mobility shift assays were used to examine the DNA binding activity of ArsR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArsR , ArsB , and ArsC protein products are indicated by the arrowheads on the right side of the figure .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8764681" target="_blank">8764681</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this study truncated ArsR proteins were produced with the objective of investigating the relationship between dimerization and function of the ArsR protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>Dimerization of ArsR was investigated using the yeast two-hybrid system in which the ArsR protein was fused to the Saccharomyces cerevisiae GAL4 DNA-binding domain and GAL4 activation domain to produce chimeric proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>In each panel , lanes 1 and 2 contain the A and C reactions from nucleotide sequencing of the same fragment ; lanes 3 -- 8 contain DNase I-treated DNA ; lanes 3 and 8 , no ArsR protein ; lane 4 , 0.5 mg of ArsR ; lane 5 , 2 mg of ArsR ; lane 6 , 4 mg of ArsR ; lane 7 , 8 mg of ArsR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>From analysis of the fusions , residues between 83 and 102 of the ArsR protein are perhaps involved in DNA binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vitro effect of inducer on DNA and ArsR altered protein interaction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArsR protein-DNA interactions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArsR protein-DNA interaction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
