			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">ArsR protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>In essentially all cases examined , amino acid substitutions placed into the cents rst coordination shell of metal li-gands in any SmtB/ArsR repressor give rise to a repressor that maintains high a ⁄ nity for the O/P in the absence of metal ions in vitro and in vivo , but is totally or partially insensitive to negative regulation of DNA-binding by metal ions [ 24,27,28,39,45 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Stoichiometry of SmtB/ArsR repressor ^ O/P binding Equilibrium analytical ultracentrifugation studies reveal that SmtB/ArsR repressors are weakly dissociable homo-dimers , in both the metal-bound and metal-free states ( Kdimer , Fig. 6 ) [ 23,32,39,55 ] , with the monomer ^ dimer equilibrium linked to site-speci cents c DNA-binding equilibria .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>A detailed multiple sequence alignment , carried out in the context of the high resolution structures of one or more apo - and metallated SmtB/ArsR repressors , using for example an evolutionary trace method , will reveal not only those residues that are common to all family members ( these presumably play a role in maintaining tertiary or quaternary structure or are conserved as part of the KR DNA-recognition helix ) , but other key residues outside those that are required to bind metal that co-vary with the evolution of new metal-binding or functional speci cents cities , e.g. , K3N vs. K5 sensors ( cf. Fig. 1 ) [ 59,60 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , the fact that both the putative metal-binding motif ELCVCDL and the critical His-50 residue in the putativeDNA-bindinghelix - turn-helix motif identified in the R773-encoded ArsR protein ( Shi et al. 1994 ) are also conserved in the chromosomal ars homolog implies similar DNA - and metalloid-binding properties of the chromosomal arsR gene product .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8764681" target="_blank">8764681</a>]<br></li>
<li>X-ray absorption spectroscopy of As ( III ) - ArsR revealed that As ( III ) was coordinated via three cysteine thiolate ligands within the putative K3 helix ( Fig. 5 ) , two of which were clearly derived from the 30ELCVCD35 motif [ 46 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Note that the ligands associated with the putative K5 helices are not conserved in any ArsR ( cf. Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Early reports on ArsR corroborated this hypothesis since substitution of one or both cysteines with non-met-al-liganding residues in the 30ELCVCD35 motif inhibited the ability of arsenate salts to dissociate ArsR from the ars O/P [ 46 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcriptional activation of lacZ reporter indicated that dimerization of the ArsR is stable in yeast .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , the ArsR repressors are most likely functional homodimers , which indicates the existence of a dimerization domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>Plasmid pETRN41 , expressing amino-terminal ArsR truncation of residues 1 -- 40 , was constructed by cloning a PCR fragment produced using oligonucleotide P4 as the forward primer and P13 as the reverse primer into vector pET28a .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>Ultimately , only experimental determination of the three dimensional structure of the ArsR protein will verify these predictions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051064" target="_blank">8051064</a>]<br></li>
<li>Six translational fusions were obtained , with the fusion sites from the 10th to 105th amino acyl residue of the 117-residue ArsR protein ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus the p-lactamase fusion analysis establishes that ArsR protein Is located in the cytosol .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>Additionally , the possible participation of the hydroxyl oxygens of Ser-43 and Ser-48 , residues conserved in the five known ArsR proteins , was investigated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Dimerization of ArsR was investigated using the yeast two-hybrid system in which the ArsR protein was fused to the Saccharomyces cerevisiae GAL4 DNA-binding domain and GAL4 activation domain to produce chimeric proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>The putative ArsR HTH is underlined .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245262" target="_blank">18245262</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is consistent with the results of the present study that demonstrate that a core sequence of approximately 80 residues is sufficient for all of the regulatory properties of the ArsR repressor : dimerization , DNA-binding , and metal recognition .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ArsR sequence ELC32VC34DL has been proposed to form a portion of the metal-binding domain , and a putative helix-turn-helix DNA-binding motif from residues 38 to 54 has been identified in ArsR ( 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>The DNA-binding properties of the altered ArsR proteins and their interaction with inducer were determined .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>The effect of PAO on the DNA-binding properties of ArsR proteins with substitutions of cysteine residues was determined ( Fig. 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , removal of the first 11 or 40 residues of ArsR abolished interaction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine residues in ArsR involved in coordination with As ( III ) , interaction with PAO was measured using PAO immobilized on a matrix .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>PAO-ArsR interaction chromatography .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>When the mature form of b-lactamase was fused to the ArsR protein at residue 92 , 101 , 104 , or 114 , expression of the chimeric protein was still inducible , indicating that residues 92 to the C terminus are not required for ArsR function .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>From analysis of the fusions , residues between 83 and 102 of the ArsR protein are perhaps involved in DNA-binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the possiblity that the ArsR-p-iactamase chimera with 102 residues of ArsR might have repressor activity that a truncated protein with only 102 residues of ArsR does not exhibit can not be exduded .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fusions containing less than 102 residues of the 117-residue ArsR protein were constitutive .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was found that chimeric proteins with p-lactamase fused near the Cterminal end ( residues 102 or 105 of 117 ) of the ArsR protein retained regulatory activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , removal of ArsR residues 1 -- 8 or 90 -- 117 does not prevent metal recognition nor the ability of metal to dissociate the repressor from the promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results of deletion analysis of the arsR gene using the yeast two-hybrid system show that the amino-terminal 8 residues and carboxyl-terminal 28 residues are not required for dimerization of ArsR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results indicated that residues 1 -- 8 and 90 -- 117 are not required for ArsR dimerization .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results suggest that amino-terminal residues 1 -- 8 and carboxyl-terminal residues 90 -- 117 of ArsR are not required for dimerization .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>Chimeras with [ i-lacta-mase fused closer to the W-terminus ( residues 10-83 of ArsR ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>The smallest is ArsR of the archebacterium Methanococcus jannaschii , with only 89 residues ( 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>That homolog aligns with residues 2 -- 90 of the E. coli ArsR , with all of the identities between ArsR residues 9 and 89 ( Fig. 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>In R773 ArsR , there are 5 cysteine , 10 serine , and 2 threonine residues ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>To exclude the possibility that the phenotype of these ArsR derivatives resulted from the substitution of the bulky aromatic groups of tyrosine or phenylalanine for the two cysteine thiolates , these two cysteine residues in ArsR were changed to glycine residues , individually or together , by site-directed mutagenesis , producing three altered ArsR proteins : C32G , C34G , and C32G/C34G .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>Second , we have shown that Cys-32 and Cys-34 of R773 ArsR are part of a metal-binding domain involved in induction ( Shi et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArsR residues Cys-32 and Cys-34 were previously identified as involved in induction by arsenite and antimonite , suggesting coordination between As ( III ) and the two cysteine thiolates .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArsR proteins containing any two of the three cysteine residues Cys-32 , Cys-34 , and Cys-37 bound to the resin .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="DOM_collapse_similarity" for="dom_similarity_41">
In addition to Cys-32 and Cys-34 , ArsR contains three other cysteine resi-dues , Cys-37 , Cys-108 , and Cys-116 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></label>
