			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">ArsR evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>reguaor000y proteinso , ArsB fooily signature ] ( 00 % match .4 Simoilarto oeoorol AtsR proteins :0 ARSRBECOLI ( SW ) 117 E046he48ch00 .401 ) ArsR , transcriptionl regolator 77.0 % ARSR-STAAU ( SW ) 104 Sta.phy1ococcus aureus Ars.tra , nscriptonaol activatoo 41.0 % ABSRBSTAXY ( SW ) 104 Staphylococcus xvosuoo ArsR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8041620" target="_blank">8041620</a>]<br></li>
<li>Given the high degree of sequence similarity ( 25 ^ 50 % identity ) and the lack of a need to introduce signi cents cant gaps in a multiple sequence alignment ( Fig. 1 ) , threading of the amino acid sequence of E. coli R773 ArsR [ 44 ] , S. aureus pI258 CadC [ 40 ] and M. tuberculosis NmtR [ 27 ] through the structure of apo-SmtB [ 41 ] has allowed the generation of robust , albeit low resolution , models of these homodimeric repressors .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>The E. coli chromosomal arsR gene encodes a 13-kDa protein , ArsR , in which 75 % of the residues ( 88 of 117 ) are identical to those of the plasmid R773 repressor in primary amino acid sequence but only 26 % ( 34 of 117 ) are identical to the staphylococcal plasmids pI258 or pSX267 ArsR proteins ( Carlin et al. , 1995 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>The only protein to which the ArsR protein shows similarity is the CadC protein of the plasmid-encoded cadmium resist-ance determinant ( Nucifora et ai .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1838573" target="_blank">1838573</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sequence alignment of YgaV , using ClustalW ( 6 ) , with other small regulatory proteins also bearing an ArsR helix-turn-helix ( HTH ) motif ( Fig. 2 ) , shows that YgaV has greater identity ( 30 % ) with HlyU ( 18 ) of Vibrio cholerae , NolR ( 13 ) of Rhizobium meliloti , PagR ( 10 ) of Bacillus anthracis , and SoxR ( 2 , 14 ) of Pseudaminobacter salicylatoxidans than with the SmtB/ArsR regulatory proteins ( 4 ) ( SmtB , ZiaR , ArsR1 , ArsR2 , ArsR , and CadC ; 17 % identities ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245262" target="_blank">18245262</a>]<br></li>
<li>Structural studies of SmtB/ArsR family members Q resolution X-ray crystallographic structure of dimeric , apo-SmtB revealed that SmtB is an elongated dimer with a two-fold axis of symmetry consisting of cents ve K-helices and two L-strands arranged into an K1-K2-K3-KR-L1-L2-K5-fold [ 41 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>This DNA binding domain , particularly the sequence of the proposed DNA recognition K-helix ( KR ) , is also highly conserved throughout the SmtB / ArsR family and is one of the distinguishing characteristics that de cents ne membership ( cf. Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>His-50 is in the second helix of the predicted helix-turn-helix DNA binding motif and isconserved in othermembers of the ArsR family except for the SmtBprotein ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8051064" target="_blank">8051064</a>]<br></li>
<li>The other founding member of this family is the plasmid - or chromosomally encoded ArsR that acts as the arsenic/antimony-responsive repressor of the ars operon in E. coli [ 33 ] , and other bacteria ( Fig. 2 ) [ 34 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the ArsR family of transcriptional repressors , both arsenic/antimony and cadmium/zinc responsive repressors have this cysteine pair .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>This 13-kDa protein belongs to the ArsR family of metalloregulatory proteins that respond to a variety of metals including As ( III ) , Sb ( III ) , Cd ( II ) , and Zn ( II ) ( 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>ZntR , a member of the ArsR family , regulates the expression of zntA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11831459" target="_blank">11831459</a>]<br></li>
<li>The closest homologue of zntA , cadA from Staphylococcus aureus ( Nucifora et al. , 1989 ) , is regulated by a repressor CadC ( Endo and Silver , 1995 ) , a member of the ArsR family of transcriptional regulators ( Shi et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10048032" target="_blank">10048032</a>]<br></li>
<li>The chromosomal ArsR is a member of the ArsR family of metalloregulatory proteins ( 3 , 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>The protein is the best characterized member of the ArsR family of metalloregulatory proteins ( Shi et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8621591" target="_blank">8621591</a>]<br></li>
<li>These are all members of the ArsR family of regulatory proteins ( Shi et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other members of the ArsR family include Cd21/Zn21 regulatory proteins ( Yoon et al. , 1991 ; Ivey et al. , 1992 ; Morby et al. , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>In fact , several repressor proteins in this family do utilize ligands from this ` box ' including ArsR and CadC proteins ; however , it is now known that this parallel can not be made to all other members of the family [ 39,45,46 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>We have postulated that members of the ArsR family of repressor proteins should have at least three domains , a metal binding domain , a DNA-binding domain , and a dimerization domain ( 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>We would propose that all members of the ArsR family of metalloregulatory proteins contain at least four domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8576202" target="_blank">8576202</a>]<br></li>
<li>This interaction is negatively affected by Ni ( II ) or Co ( II ) binding , a pattern functionally similar to that of the structurally distinct SmtB/ArsR family of transcription factors ( reviewed in 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18505253" target="_blank">18505253</a>]<br></li>
<li>SmtB binds zinc and other heavy metals and belongs to the ArsR family of metallorepressors , which control mainly prokaryotic metal resistance operons ( 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10816566" target="_blank">10816566</a>]<br></li>
<li>The SmtB / ArsR proteins , perhaps distantly related to the MerR family , function exclusively as transcriptional repressors and include Synechococcus sp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
