<li>The SmtB/ArsR family of metalloregulatory transcriptional repressors : structural insights into prokaryotic metal resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245262" target="_blank">18245262</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Overview of the SmtB/ArsR family Individual members of the SmtB/ArsR family clearly derive from a common evolutionary origin , with members that exhibit known or postulated metal selectivities clustering on a rooted , phylogenetic tree ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>These studies suggest that a similar tertiary and quaternary structural fold characterizes individual members of the entire SmtB/ArsR family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Amino acid sequence alignment of the SmtB/ArsR family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Overview of the SmtB/ArsR family ... .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Structural studies of SmtB/ArsR family members ... .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Identi cents cation of two distinct metal-sensing sites within a conserved structural sca ¡ old A highly conserved ELCV ( C/G ) D motif termed the ` metal binding box ' was initially identi cents ed in members of the SmtB/ArsR family ( Fig. 5 ) [ 9 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is notable that the M. tuberculosis ge-nome encodes 10 putative SmtB/ArsR family members [ 27 ] , most of which do not precisely cents t the K3N and K5 metal binding site signatures documented here .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other common regulator families are ArsR ( 175 ) , AsnC ( 140 ) , Crp ( 233 ) , DeoR ( 17 ) , GntR ( 29 , 104 , 213 ) , IclR ( 214 ) , LacI ( 253 ) , LuxR/UphA ( 112 ) , LysR ( 111 ) , MarR ( 56 ) , MerR ( 107 ) , NtrC ( 189 ) , TetR ( 198 ) , YedF/YeeD/YhhP ( 14 ) , and YhdG/YjbN/YohI ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>We identiﬁed a high proportion of TFs belonging to the AsnC , ArsR , MarR , TetR/AcrR , BirA , AraC/XylS , Fur , LysR , and PhoU families in bacteria and archaea .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15556475" target="_blank">15556475</a>]<br></li>
<li>For instance , proteins classiﬁed in the Fur and PhoU families regulate iron and phosphate metabolism , the AsnC and MarR families belong to the earliest repressor super-group ( Pérez - Rueda and Collado-Vides , 2001 ) , while the ArsR family contains the shortest repressor proteins described so far ( Pérez - Rueda and Collado-Vides , 2000 ; Sato and Kobayashi , 1998 ) , very close in length to the proposed hypothetical ancestor of TFs .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15556475" target="_blank">15556475</a>]<br></li>
