<li>While ArsR is a trans-acting inducerresponsive repressor , ArsD is an inducer-independent protein controlling basal and upper-level expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19484295" target="_blank">19484295</a>]<br></li>
<li>It encodes an arsenic-inducibletrans-acting repressor ( ArsR ) , controlling the basal level of expression of the operon ( San Francisco et al. 1990 ; Wu and Rosen 1991 , 1993 ~ ) a ; negative regulator ( ArsD ) that independently controls the upper level of expression of the operon ( Wu and Rosen 1993b ) ; an arsenite - and antimonite-stimulatedATPase ( ArsA ) ( Rosen et al. 1988 ; Mei-Hsu et al. 1991 ) ; a membrane pump for efflux of arsenite and antimonite ions ( ArsB ) ( Wu et al. 1992 ; Dey and Rosen 1995 ) ; and an arsenate reductase ( ArsC ) ( Rosen et al. 1991 ; Gladysheva et al. 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8764681" target="_blank">8764681</a>]<br></li>
<li>The product of the first gene of the operon , the 117-residue ArsR protein , has been shown to be a trans-acting repressor that senses environmental As ( III ) and Sb ( III ) ( 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9188467" target="_blank">9188467</a>]<br></li>
<li>These codes for a regulatory protein ( ArsR ) arsenite ( As ( III ) ) - responsive repressor of transcription and an arsenate permease ( ArsB ) regulates for an arsenite speciﬁc transmembrane pump .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24464705" target="_blank">24464705</a>]<br></li>
